Located in Big Sky country of northwest New South Wales, Ngiyaani is a 254ha perennial native grasses grazing property being intentionally cared for utilising regenerative agriculture, ethical animal welfare and biodiversity.
Ngiyaani is home to Sarah Ferguson, Peter Long, a large community of family, friends, and kindred souls and many beloved sentient animals, including those in our Big Little Lowline stud of purebred Australian Lowline cattle — a sweet natured beefy and compact heritage breed with pure Aberdeen Angus ancestry.
Despite 10 years of drought in the 16 years since purchased, Ngiyaani has responded magnificently to being in partnership with Nature.Our key programs/projects have been aimed at restoring landscape function on what was the most degraded piece of land in the Namoi Valley (42K sq km) when purchased in 2007. This has been achieved using adaptive multi-paddock grazing of cattle after subdividing the original 5 paddocks into 18 then 36 paddocks whilst turning 18kms of contour banks into leaky weirs that keep rainfall on farm instead of diverting it off-farm. No inputs or chemicals used. Currently enhancing gains so far with foliar applications of extract from Johnson Su Compost.['Regenerative Practices']{'Facebook': 'https://www.facebook.com/profile.php?id=100093770433007', 'Email': 'mailto:peter@ngiyaani.com.au', 'Website': 'https://www.ngiyaani.com.au/'}

Blue Marble Farm is a small family-owned, self-sufficient regenerative farm using permaculture, bio-dynamics, holistic management and chemical-free growing to produce fruit, veg & herbs. We farm, restore, and live to improve the Earth. Our actions consider all the generations to come that will benefit and continue to improve and enrich a world with abundant food, a healthy environment, and rich communities. We spread the "how" of what we do in easy-to-understand formats and implement to increase food localisation and seasonal awareness for better environmental and human health — from teaching how to grow, eat, preserve, and share.Offering farm tours, permaculture coaching and workshops on cheesemaking, fermentation, resilience practices, homesteading skills and farming with nature.
We have been a case study for Southern Cross University's Regenerative Agriculture Mentor Program and now share all we can with those wanting to know more about the practical applications.
Our farm is always in a state of experimentation as we learn. We are always exploring ways to improve.['Regenerative Practices']{'Instagram': 'https://instagram.com/blue_marble_farm', 'Facebook': 'https://www.facebook.com/profile.php?id=100068959493508', 'Email': 'mailto:bluemarblefarmoz@gmail.com', 'Website': 'https://www.bluemarblefarm.com.au/'}

and packing facility, our 4Goods Meathouse.
In August of this year our vision became a reality, and with the support of our community and a crowdfunding campaign, we get our facility up and running!
We are working towards establishing a commercial kitchen to work in partnership with the Meathouse, along with a workshop and education venue, to enable us to share the story, learnings, opportunities, and regenerative practices of all that we do at Echo Valley.['Ecological Practices (certifications)', 'Regenerative Practices']{'Instagram': 'https://www.instagram.com/echovalleyfarmer/', 'Facebook': 'https://www.sustainabletable.org.au/www.facebook.com/echovalleyfarm/', 'Email': 'mailto:echovalleyorders@gmail.com', 'Website': 'https://www.echovalley.com.au/'}

Entangled is a syntropic agroforestry consultancy business. The focus of Entangled is designing homesteads, suburban micro-forest systems, and broad acre regenerative agroforestry. Our HQ features a forest system with native species informing the primary framework and support networks for a biodiverse, resilient and medicinal ecology. Resources derived are traded locally and within a gift-economy paradigm.
Entangled has the objective of creating ecosystems that provide a plurality of benefits and resources - many beyond the scope of simply food. The business’ objective is reintegrating humanity as a keystone species, of realigning with nature as protagonists rather than antagonists. It attempts to cultivate beauty and primarily focuses on building fecundity, ecological literacy and supporting the needs of local non-human organisms, with human benefits as a secondary outcome. It aims to build around the concept of community resilience and mutual reciprocity instead of self-sufficiency.
Entangled also operates a small private nursery, cultivating different forest species for use in agroforestry installations.Entangled primarily consults with private landholders who are in the genesis phases of developing their projects. We also engage with local community groups to develop accessible forest ecologies to service metropolitan communities.['Regenerative Practices']{'Instagram': 'https://instagram.com/the_wondering_river', 'Email': 'mailto:alasdair.bednall@gmail.com'}

Green Earth Farms consists of two couples running a certified organic farm in Pimlico, NSW. The farm has been organically certified since 1991, we took over 3 years ago. As well as growing produce to supply local markets and the local community, we have opened a farm shop which supplies organic products sourced as locally as possible. We run courses for the local community for growing, composting and biodynamics. We aim to supply the freshest, cleanest, affordable and sustainable produce to our community and beyond, educating them in organic farming practices and the benefits of eating organic.Wardell Core - planting projects & community garden. We have donated 10 large growing beds to The Wardell Core; a charity started to help victims of the recent flood disaster.
Composting/growing/biodynamics courses — ongoing courses offered to the local community to educate them about various practices they can take away to their own gardens.
Mushroom compost - using our spent mushroom bags and green waste to make compost.['Ecological Practices (certifications)', 'Regenerative Practices']{'Instagram': 'https://www.instagram.com/vegoutwithpop', 'Facebook': 'https://www.facebook.com/vegoutwithpop', 'Email': 'mailto:info@greenearthfarms.com.au', 'Website': 'https://www.greenearthfarms.com.au/'}

We supply ethically-raised, nutrient-dense & diverse sheep & pork products to the New England region of NSW, from our farm to your door.
We deeply consider the impact of each of our decisions and have designed a system that increases biodiversity, does away with nasty chemicals, fights climate change with natural carbon sequestering and reduces waste wherever possible. From our farm practices to cut selection and packaging, every decision is based on how we can offer your family a top-quality product with genuinely impeccable flavour.At Balala Station we farm holistically in nature's image, building natural capital, fostering biodiversity, and eliminating unnecessary chemicals.
We are Land 2 Market Ecologically Certified which underpins our company's holistic context.['Ecological Outcomes Verified (EOV)', 'Regenerative Practices']{'Instagram': 'https://www.instagram.com/balala_station/', 'Facebook': 'https://www.facebook.com/balalastation', 'Email': 'mailto:richard@balala.com.au', 'Website': 'https://www.balala.com.au/'}

Door – In 2023 we opened our ‘Bakery Door’ offering our Certified Organic sourdough directly to the local community. It allows us to tell a fuller story of our vision and share the unrivalled enjoyment of oven-fresh bread.
Waste & waste recovery – We bake to order, eschewing the common bakery practice of ‘baking to waste’. Any remaining food waste is collected by a local farmer who also provides transport services to us.
Bio-dynamic products and ingredients – In 2020, we launched our first Certified Bio-dynamic single-origin sourdough. Every Certified Organic product in our range also contains Bio-dynamic ingredients; best practice Organics.['Ecological Practices (certifications)']{'Instagram': 'https://www.instagram.com/zeallybaysourdough/', 'Facebook': 'https://www.facebook.com/zbsourdough/', 'Email': 'mailto:sales@zeallybaysourdough.com.au', 'Website': 'https://zeallybaysourdough.com.au/'}

Learning from Nature is a social enterprise providing an innovative solution to food insecurity and the climate and environmental crisis.
We support farmers and food gardeners to understand and tackle the root causes of their poor growing conditions by repairing the ecosystems underpinning their production systems. We use this eco-logical approach because the often-cited goals of regenerative agriculture - improving biodiversity, organic matter, carbon, water infiltration, etc., are the products and services of functioning ecosystems. We need ecosystems that work for these to improve.
By supporting growers to restore these free ecological services in their veggie gardens, orchards, and fields, they reduce their dependence on fertilisers, pest controls, and other external inputs, create more resilient growing conditions, and supply essential environmental services such as biodiversity and carbon sequestration as natural by-products.We're scaling up and accelerating our support to farmers and food gardeners using our handbooks and courses by forming partnerships with international organisations and locally with NRM groups, food networks, and environmental organisations (with restorative food programs).[]{'Email': 'mailto:info@learningfromnature.com.au', 'Website': 'https://www.learningfromnature.com.au/'}

As one of Australia’s earliest organic meat producers, we transitioned our family farm — Cherry Tree Downs — in Victoria’s picturesque South Gippsland region to organic farming in the early 1990s. We did this to optimise the taste and health benefits of our meat and reflect our commitment to animal welfare and sustainability.
Today we run a fully sustainable farm that produces award-winning lamb and beef for local and international customers. We also offer top quality certified organic pork and chicken, sourced from like-minded family farms in Victoria and Queensland.
Our mission is to provide our customers with the finest quality ethically and sustainably raised organic meat and connect them with their food sources.Carbon Sequestration Project - drawing carbon out of the atmosphere and down into the soil to promote the soil biology and improve our production. We registered 5 years ago (base sample taken) and in January 2023 we resampled to check in on how much carbon we have sequestered.['Ecological Practices (certifications)', 'Regenerative Practices']{'Instagram': 'https://www.instagram.com/cherrytreeorganics/', 'Facebook': 'https://www.facebook.com/cherrytreeorganics/', 'Email': 'mailto:hello@cherrytreeorganics.com.au', 'Website': 'https://www.cherrytreeorganics.com.au/'}

The Food Embassy is a social enterprise on the Fleurieu Peninsula in SA, founded in 2016. Our vision is to support and strengthen local food communities that restore and nurture our connection to ourselves, our community and our planet. We acknowledge and respect that we work on Kaurna/Peramangk and Ngarrindjeri country, and we engage and support First Nations leadership, culture, self-determination and innovation wherever possible.
We activate and regenerate local food systems by supporting community-led projects and mentoring individuals to build local resilient food communities. Critical to regeneration is knowledge, and we offer training in food systems to community, government and business. We also run workshops and events to increase community awareness around food systems and to connect eaters to producers and growers. At the heart of all this work is strong relationships and trust that enable meaningful activation and change to build a fairer food system for all.We are currently taking the lead role as the regional local food activator, supporting and strengthening the Hills and Fleurieu food system by identifying the needs and opportunities for investment and activation. Key to this role is working with a collective of organisations to enable a model/framework that will allow this work to continue into the future.
Other exciting projects are looking at a collaborative eco logistics solution for the region, and we have another popular 'Women in Farming' event where we hear from local women farmers and their stories.['Funded by Sustainable Table']{'Instagram': 'https://www.instagram.com/thefoodembassy/', 'Facebook': 'https://www.facebook.com/foodembassycommunity/', 'Email': 'mailto:liz@thefoodembassy.org', 'Website': 'https://www.thefoodembassy.org/'}

Southern Seagreens is the coming together of three friends with a shared love for the sea. By combining our skills, we realised we could work with the sun and sea and learn to farm native seaweed at Flinders, Victoria.
Our primary aim is to grow the most sustainable food possible. With the planet on track to host nearly 10 billion humans by 2050, we need to find smarter and more sustainable ways to produce nutritious food and get it to market. Seaweed requires no soil, fresh water or fertilizers. It’s a zero-input crop and it's packed with protein and important nutrients for human health. It also improves the marine eco-system as it grows. With ideal growing conditions here in Victoria, we think kelp might soon play an important role in our local food system.
We were lucky enough to be awarded Mornington Peninsula Shire’s Climate Action Grant last year and this has enabled us to establish a kelp nursery on the Mornington Peninsula. We’re now able to seed juvenile kelp onto twine that we can then take to our aquaculture site off Flinders to grow to maturity. We also dive for Wakame (an introduced but high-quality kelp) in local waters that we are turning into nutritious food products. Removing Wakame aids the regeneration of native kelp populations that have been impacted by rising sea temperatures and invasive sea urchins in recent times.Southern Seagreens is committed to exploring ways to collaborate and share their learnings to support Traditional Owners and First Nations enterprises in this space and are in early conversations with Traditional Owners about opportunities for this.['Regenerative Practices']{'Instagram': 'https://www.instagram.com/southern_seagreens/', 'Email': 'mailto:cam@southernseagreens.com', 'Website': 'https://www.southernseagreens.com/'}

Timbarra Farm grows organic vegetables, berries and flowers in the Yarra Valley. We sell to local restaurants, provide a community veggie box and attend Healesville organic farmers market seasonally.
Some of our produce is also sold to an aggregator who supplies many Melbourne restaurants.Our ongoing project is to grow veggies better!
We have no funding from any organisation currently.['Regenerative Practices']{'Instagram': 'https://www.instagram.com/timbarra_farm/', 'Facebook': 'https://www.facebook.com/timbarrafarm/', 'Email': 'mailto:timbarrafarm@gmail.com'}

Milkwood is dedicated to teaching and sharing permaculture skills. We inspire and enable households to take action to cultivate resilient communities and ecosystems. We energise individuals to engage with the social and environmental challenges we all face.
We offer a mix of free permaculture resources and guides, extensive articles and how-tos, short courses and fully mentored online courses.Our flagship courses include:
Permaculture Living, a 12-week program to build habits and skills focused on permaculture principles and do-able actions;
Home Mushroom Cultivation, an 8-week program to learn low-waste household mushroom growing; and,
Organic Vegetable Gardening, an 8-week program to kickstart a home vegetable garden from planning to harvest, with organic principles.[]{'Instagram': 'https://www.instagram.com/milkwood/', 'Facebook': 'https://www.facebook.com/Milkwood?fref=ts', 'Email': 'mailto:hello@milkwood.net', 'Website': 'https://www.milkwood.net/'}

We grow soil-grown microgreens in two unheated greenhouses on our 1000-square-metre property in Canberra. We currently supply about 30 restaurants and cafes. Each week we collect our Australian-made, recycled plastic trays, which we wash and reuse. We compost the spent organic soil mix.
Our block is developed using Permaculture principles. There are over 50 fruit trees, nuts, berries, vegetables, chickens, bees and working rabbits.
Fiona Buining recently completed a Churchill Fellowship investigating vocational pathways for aspiring urban farmers.My vision is to see the establishment of urban farm training ventures based on the findings of my Churchill Fellowship. I specialise in soil-grown microgreens, run workshops and tours, and am available as a consultant.[]{'Instagram': 'https://www.instagram.com/ainslieurbanfarm', 'Email': 'mailto:info@ainslieurbanfarm.com.au', 'Website': 'https://www.ainslieurbanfarm.com.au/'}

Ethically produced healthy meat for your family. Tarinore Farm specialises in producing quality, ethically-raised beef and lamb grown on pastures. We work with nature to produce a highly nutritious and healthy product.
We provide fresh and sustainable alternatives to conventionally grown meat; we are committed to doing things differently. Farming using regenerative principles and practices, we aim to improve the environment and grow healthy products for you.
We focus on regenerating our soils and our local ecosystem to grow better pastures for our animals. Through the development of our whole system's biodiversity, our animals graze on diverse pastures every day, producing healthy meat for you.We provide on-farm learning opportunities for schools, universities and training organisations to extend the learning of regenerative agriculture.['Regenerative Practices']{'Instagram': 'https://www.instagram.com/tarinorefarm/', 'Facebook': 'https://www.facebook.com/tarinorefarm', 'Email': 'mailto:farmgate@tarinorefarm.com.au', 'Website': 'https://www.tarinorefarm.com.au/'}

Ripple Farm Landscape Healing Hub is a 100-acre property in Richmond, Tasmania, managed by author Rachael Treasure and Daniel Loré. Together we have been demonstrating the repair of previously lifeless soil, using multi-species managed grazing, Natural Sequence Farming and holistic practices, back to native grassland and wetland, with food farming included.
Ripple Farm Landscape Healing Hub hosts charity events, art exhibitions, film nights and farmer education days. School groups also experience a new vision for agriculture upon thriving soils.
We are working to directly sell ethically grown and diversely grazed beef, lamb and eggs via Open Food Network.We are developing a collaborative not-for-profit vision for Ripple Farm - the 'Ripple Effect'. The aim is to synergistically marry creativity, art, spirituality, education and storytelling with regenerative farming systems, community collaboration and food sovereignty awareness within this multi-purpose space.['Regenerative Practices']{'Facebook': 'https://www.facebook.com/rach.treasure', 'Email': 'mailto:rachael.treasure@gmail.com', 'Website': 'https://www.rachaeltreasure.com/'}

Kinsfolk Farm is a 2-acre market garden located on Wadawurrung country in Moriac, Victoria, run by Bridie Cotter and Tom Gaunt. We employ organic principles to grow delicious and nutrient-dense vegetables to sell directly to our local community around the greater Geelong and surf coast region.
We are two young farmers with backgrounds in design and music, who packed up out of the big smoke and landed back in some familiar childhood territory. With little supply of fresh organic veg in the area, we set out to find a patch of land to grow our own and share it with others with a similar love for food and cooking. We now lease a pocket of fertile soil from the Menzies family in Moriac.
We grow over forty varieties of seasonal vegetables and herbs which you can find every Saturday at the Torquay Farmer's Market.Home Harvest is our first foray into writing and publishing. Alongside Hardie Grant books, we have created a fun, practical and easy-to-read deck of cards to help you plant and grow your own kitchen garden. Each card is beautifully illustrated by the phenomenal Edith Rewa, making this a stunning gift for every gardener or soon-to-be gardener in your life.['Regenerative Practices']{'Instagram': 'http://instagram.com/kinsfolk_farm', 'Facebook': 'http://facebook.com/kinsfolk_farm', 'Email': 'mailto:kinsfolkfarm@gmail.com', 'Website': 'http://kinsfolkfarm.com.au/'}

