Regenerative Produce Discovery Project: is aiming to increase demand and market access for Australian regenerative producers and products by making it easier for priority buyers to discover, understand and purchase from them.
Victorian Community Food Enterprise Rapid Needs and Value Assessment: Open Food Network will lead a ‘rapid needs and value assessment’ project for the sector to inform a collective bid for funding/support from government and philanthropy.['Funded by Sustainable Table']{'Instagram': 'https://www.instagram.com/openfoodnetworkaus/', 'Facebook': 'https://www.facebook.com/openfoodnetworkaus/', 'Email': 'mailto:hello@openfoodnetwork.org.au', 'Website': 'https://about.openfoodnetwork.org.au/'}

Willum Warrain Bush Nursery specialises in growing plants from the Mornington Peninsula, one and a half hours south of Melbourne. Our social enterprise is 100% Aboriginal community-owned and led, intent on creating employment pathways for local Aboriginal people. We share the cultural uses, stories and meanings of these plants, many of which are significant to Aboriginal people across South East Australia. Our aim is to promote healing country locally and regionally.Healing Water Country — with the Western Port Biosphere, we are delivering a project creating a bio-link corridor linking Warringine Creek to RAMSAR-protected Western Port Bay.
With Unison/City of Melbourne — providing design advice and plants for rooftop gardens in CBD for social housing projects.
Main supplier of local Indigenous plants for Service Stream who manage 80 km of Peninsula Link freeway verges.['Funded by Sustainable Table']{'Instagram': 'https://www.instagram.com/willumwarrain/', 'Facebook': 'https://www.facebook.com/WillumWarrain', 'Email': 'mailto:eo@willumwarrain.org.au', 'Website': 'https://www.willumwarrain.org.au/'}

Our mission is to grow conscious farmers, empowering them with knowledge, experience, community and connection so that they can contribute to the regeneration of land and a sovereign food future. As farmers and entrepreneurs, we are passionate about providing a more approachable entry into farming by creating safe spaces for aspiring farmers to grow, learn and connect with others, as well as exploring the potential of collaborative farming models and the mechanisms by which we steward, access, share and perceive land.Our Pop-Up Garlic Farmer Program runs on underutilised land in and around Melbourne, guiding participants through a season of growing and selling garlic.
In 2021 we published our research report ‘Regeneration: Growing New Farmers’, which explores the opportunities and barriers for aspiring farmers - from a changing climate, accessing capital, cultural norms, our settler colonial history and Indigenous dispossession - pointing to some potential pathways going forward.
In 2023 we launched our Intermediate Farmers Program, which seeks to take aspiring farmers to the next stage by providing them with the opportunity to grow a large crop under supervision and deepen their experience.['Funded by Sustainable Table']{'Instagram': 'http://instagram.com/farmerincubator', 'Facebook': 'http://fb.com/farmerincubator', 'Email': 'mailto:hello@farmerincubator.org', 'Website': 'http://farmerincubator.org/'}

Soils for Life is an independent, non-profit organisation whose mission is to support Australian farmers to regenerate soils for resilient people, communities, businesses and landscapes. We are working to realise a world where healthy, regenerated soils and landscapes support profitable food-producing businesses, thriving and resilient regional communities, and abundant and nutritious food.

Unlike a decade ago, building soil health through regenerative farming approaches is no longer niche. Increasing numbers of farmers are looking to soil regeneration as a solution, having seen the benefits that healthy soils have brought to leading farmers around the country. However, there is a wide gap between interest and action. Changing practices involves risk and requires investment - of time, energy and money. Farmers need support to get to the point where they have confidence to take those risks and make those investments.

We believe that providing farmers with the knowledge, skills, confidence and supporting social infrastructure they need to lead a national effort to rebuild and restore soils will strengthen Australia’s response to climate change while enabling the production of healthy, plentiful food and fibre in ways that are good for farmers, communities and the planet.Our case study program provides holistic examples of soil and landscape regeneration. This program is empowering farmers to build confidence to adopt regenerative approaches to agriculture. Case studies provide the foundation for our work, because farmers learn best from other farmers. Our case study farmers provide a powerful national network of change agents willing to share knowledge and champion the cause of regeneration. We coordinate a range of other projects supporting peer learning communities for soil and landscape regeneration, and farmer capacity building for soil and landscape literacy. These on-ground activities inform our advocacy to influence researchers, government and industry.[]{'Instagram': 'https://www.instagram.com/soilsforlife/', 'Facebook': 'https://www.facebook.com/SoilsforLife', 'Email': 'mailto:eli.court@soilsforlife.org.au', 'Website': 'http://soilsforlife.org.au/'}

Food Connect Shed exists to create a more equitable, regenerative and healthy food system by providing infrastructure to connect growers to eaters, a home for ethical food entrepreneurs to be able to collaborate, and a place where our community can belong.
The Shed is a community-owned warehouse in Brisbane with over 500 ‘careholders’ (shareholders) invested in the business, and over 30 food enterprise, nonprofit and social enterprise tenants leasing space and sharing commercial kitchens, cold rooms and storage facilities.
The Shed was initiated by the Food Connect Foundation which supports community-led food enterprises, along with providing education and advocacy services.After running the event space for four years, we’re adding a community-scale flour mill, a local food retail shop, bar and café. We'll be employing a values-based supply chain coordinator to facilitate the soft infrastructure required to create a thriving ecosystem. This will feed into a national replication strategy, that’s open-sourced to communities.['Funded by Sustainable Table']{'Instagram': 'https://www.instagram.com/foodconnectshed/', 'Facebook': 'https://www.linkedin.com/company/foodconnectshed/about/', 'Email': 'mailto:hello@foodconnectshed.com.au', 'Website': 'http://www.foodconnectshed.com.au/'}
